Mapping Btnl[1,4,6] Genes to Small Intestinal Epithelium scRNA-Seq Data: Haber et. al.

philip.east@crick.ac.uk

Compiled: 09 April, 2020 @ 15:08:17

library( Seurat )
library( tidyverse )
set.seed( 1000 )
my_grey <- "#707173"
my_red <- "#e3001a"

Introduction

Presented here is a re-analysis of scRNA-Seq data from Haber et. al. A single-cell survey of the small intestinal epithelium. Here we show the expression patterns of specific Btnl genes in different intestinal cell populations reported in Haber et. al.

Btln Genes

We are interested in Btnl1/4/6.

genes <- c( "Btnl1", "Btnl4", "Btnl6" )

scRNA-Seq data

The raw data and processed cell sets can be found at GSE92332.

Read in data

We read in the raw counts contained within GSE92332_SalmHelm_UMIcounts.txt. Cell barcode, cell type and infection status labels were obtained from column headers.

sc_exprs_mat_file <- "GSE92332_SalmHelm_UMIcounts.txt"
dat <- read.delim( file = sc_exprs_mat_file )

design_l <- strsplit( colnames( dat ), "_" )
names( design_l ) <- unlist( lapply( design_l, function( x ) paste( x[ 2 ], x[ 1 ], sep = "_" ) ) )
design_df <- do.call( 'rbind', design_l ) %>%
    as.data.frame( )
colnames( design_df ) <- c( "cell_group", "barcode", "condition", "cell_type" )

colnames( dat ) <- rownames( design_df )
srat_obj <- CreateSeuratObject( counts = dat,
                               meta.data = design_df,
                               project = "haber_etal",
                               min.cells = 0,
                               min.features = 0 )

srat_obj@meta.data <- srat_obj@meta.data %>%
    rownames_to_column( var = "cell_id" ) %>%
    mutate( cell_id_tmp = cell_id ) %>%
    column_to_rownames( "cell_id_tmp" )
srat_obj

Here we check the number of genes and UMIs identified per cell. These were found to be within expected ranges.

VlnPlot( object = srat_obj,

plot1

Preprocess raw counts

Here we process the raw counts in-line with the standard Seurat workflow. We first normalise the raw counts by scaling them to 10,000 counts and applying a log transformation. We identify the 2000 most variable genes using Seurats vst method. We then scale the data prior to running PCA. The cells are then clustered and non-linear dimension reduction is applied using UMAP and the first 50 PCs.

dims_to_use <- 50
srat_obj <- NormalizeData( srat_obj, normalization.method = "LogNormalize", scale.factor = 10000 )
srat_obj <- FindVariableFeatures( object = srat_obj,
                                     selection.method = 'vst',
                                     nfeatures = 2000 )
srat_obj <- ScaleData( object = srat_obj, features = rownames(x = srat_obj ) )
srat_obj <- RunPCA( object = srat_obj, features = VariableFeatures( object = srat_obj ), verbose = FALSE )
ElbowPlot( object = srat_obj, ndims = 50 )

srat_obj <- FindNeighbors( object = srat_obj, dims = 1:dims_to_use, verbose = FALSE )
srat_obj <- FindClusters( object = srat_obj, resolution = 0.5, verbose = FALSE )
srat_obj <- RunUMAP( object = srat_obj, dims = 1:dims_to_use )

Diffusion Map

A diffusion map with published cell types in the control group.

Cell type diffusion map

dp1 <- DimPlot( object = srat_obj[, srat_obj$condition %in% "Control" ],
                reduction = 'umap', label = TRUE, group.by = "cell_type" ) +
    labs( title = "Cell Type: Control group" )
print( dp1 )

DotPlot

The expression of the Btnl genes are shown per cell type across the control group. The colour represents the mean expression across the cell types (z-score scaled). The size of the dot shows the percentage of expressing cells within each cell type.

dp <- DotPlot( srat_obj[, srat_obj$condition %in% "Control" ],
              features = rev( genes ), cols = c( "lightgrey", my_red ),
              dot.scale = 8, group.by = "cell_type" ) +
    labs( y = "Cell types", x = "Btnl[x] genes", title = "Control group" ) +
    theme( axis.text.x = element_text( angle = 90, hjust = 1 ) )
print( dp )
